Among the main activities of Europa Nostra, there are: 
i) general lobbying and structured dialogue between civil society organisations committed to cultural heritage (including the European Heritage Alliance 3.3 which has been coordinated by Europa Nostra since its creation in 2010) and the EU institutions; 
ii) celebrating excellence through the European Union Prize for Cultural Heritage/Europa Nostra Awards; 
iii) managing the "7 Most Endangered" programme with the European Investment Bank Institute as a founding partner; 
iv) organising various networking and capacity building meetings and events all over Europe, including Europa Nostra' s Annual European Heritage Congress - which took place in Turku (Finland) in 2017; 
v) communication activities, including social media and Europa Nostra's annual magazine "Heritage in Motion"; 
vi) disseminating the results of the cooperation project "Cultural Heritage Counts for Europe", which was supported by the EU Culture Programme and run in partnership with 5 other organisations from 2013-2015, e.g. through facilitating the translation of the Executive Summary.
